biomarker.info.description: Total cholesterol is a lipid (fat) molecule found in the blood, essential for building cell membranes and producing hormones. It exists in various forms, including low-density lipoprotein (LDL) and high-density lipoprotein (HDL), which play different roles in cardiovascular health.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High total cholesterol poses significant risks primarily related to cardiovascular diseases such as coronary artery disease (CAD), heart attacks, and strokes due to arterial blockages caused by plaque formation from excess LDL particles.
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low total cholesterol levels may be linked to several health risks such as hormonal imbalances affecting mood or cognitive function. Additionally, extremely low levels have been associated with an increased incidence of certain cancers and hemorrhagic strokes.
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Consume a diet rich in fruits, vegetables, whole grains 
- Include healthy fats like those found in avocados and nuts 
- Engage in regular physical activity 
- Maintain a healthy weight 
- Limit saturated fats found in red meat and full-fat dairy products
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- High intake of saturated fats from processed foods 
- Sedentary lifestyle leading to obesity 
- Smoking tobacco products 
- Excessive alcohol consumption
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Total cholesterol encompasses all types of cholesterol present in the bloodstream, including LDL, HDL, very-low-density lipoproteins (VLDL), and chylomicrons. LDL is often termed 'bad' cholesterol because high levels can lead to plaque buildup in arteries, increasing the risk of atherosclerosis—a condition characterized by narrowed arteries due to plaque accumulation. Conversely, HDL is known as 'good' cholesterol since it helps transport excess cholesterol from tissues back to the liver for excretion or recycling. The balance between these types influences overall cardiovascular risk significantly; thus measuring total cholesterol provides insight into lipid metabolism and potential disease processes.
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring total cholesterol is vital as it serves as a key indicator of cardiovascular health. Elevated levels are associated with an increased risk of heart disease and stroke, while low levels can indicate malnutrition or other health issues. Regular monitoring helps identify individuals at risk, guiding preventive measures and treatment strategies.

biomarker.info.description: Le HDL-Cholestérol, souvent désigné comme 'bon cholestérol,' est un composant des lipoprotéines de haute densité (HDL), qui sont des nanoparticules protéines-lipides. Le HDL joue un rôle crucial dans l'élimination de l'excès de cholestérol des cellules et son transport vers le foie pour excrétion, aidant ainsi à prévenir l'athérosclérose (l'accumulation de plaque dans les artères).
biomarker.info.risksHigh: Paradoxalement, des niveaux extrêmement élevés de HDL-Cholestérol ont été liés à une mortalité cardiovasculaire accrue dans certaines études, suggérant une relation en U entre le HDL-C et le risque de MCV[5](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36671490/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Des niveaux bas de HDL-Cholestérol sont associés à un risque accru de maladies cardiovasculaires, car ils peuvent indiquer une capacité réduite pour l'efflux de cholestérol et un risque accru d'athérosclérose[5](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36671490/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4005321/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- S'engager dans une activité physique régulière pour améliorer les niveaux de HDL 
- Maintenir un poids sain 
- Suivre un régime équilibré riche en fruits, légumes, et grains entiers 
- Limiter la consommation d'alcool 
- Ne pas fumer
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Mode de vie sédentaire 
- Obésité 
- Régimes riches en graisses 
- Tabagisme 
- Consommation excessive d'alcool
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Le HDL est une entité complexe avec plusieurs fonctions au-delà du simple transport du cholestérol, y compris des propriétés anti-inflammatoires et antioxydantes. Il est composé de diverses protéines et phospholipides, et sa fonctionnalité peut être influencée par des facteurs tels que les variations génétiques et le stress oxydatif[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2780869/)[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6489608/)[7](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5823773/). La capacité du HDL à faciliter l'efflux de cholestérol des macrophages est un aspect clé de son rôle protecteur contre l'athérosclérose[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6489608/)[5](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36671490/).
biomarker.info.importance: Mesurer le HDL-Cholestérol est important car il sert de biomarqueur de la santé cardiovasculaire. Des niveaux plus élevés de HDL-C sont généralement associés à un risque réduit de maladies cardiovasculaires athéroscléreuses (MCV), bien que des études récentes suggèrent que la fonction HDL peut être plus prédictive du risque de MCV que les niveaux de HDL seuls[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2780869/)[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6489608/)[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4661556/).

biomarker.info.description: Apolipoprotein B (ApoB) is a protein found in **atherogenic lipoproteins** (like LDL and VLDL), which are linked to **atherosclerosis** (the buildup of plaque in arteries). Each particle of these lipoproteins contains one ApoB molecule, making it a direct measure of the number of these particles in the blood
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High ApoB levels are linked to increased risk of cardiovascular diseases, including atherosclerosis and coronary heart disease. Elevated ApoB is a strong predictor of cardiovascular events[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10488498/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11019329/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low levels of ApoB are generally associated with reduced cardiovascular risk. However, there is limited evidence on specific health risks associated with low ApoB levels.
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a healthy diet low in saturated fats 
- Engage in regular physical activity to improve lipid profiles 
- Consider statin therapy if recommended by a healthcare provider 
- Manage weight to reduce metabolic risks
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- High intake of saturated fats and cholesterol 
- Sedentary lifestyle 
- Obesity 
- Smoking 
- Certain medications that affect lipid metabolism
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: ApoB is a key structural component of VLDL, IDL, LDL, and lipoprotein(a), which are involved in lipid transport and metabolism. It exists in two forms: apoB48, primarily in chylomicrons, and apoB100, in VLDL, IDL, and LDL. ApoB100 is more clinically relevant due to its role in atherogenesis[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8540246/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11019329/). The trapping of ApoB-containing particles in arterial walls initiates atherosclerosis[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7369156/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring ApoB is important because it provides a more accurate assessment of cardiovascular risk compared to traditional markers like LDL cholesterol. ApoB reflects the total number of atherogenic particles, which is crucial for predicting and managing cardiovascular diseases[1](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31642874/)[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8540246/)[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7369156/).

biomarker.info.description: Insulin is a hormone produced by the pancreas that regulates blood sugar levels by facilitating glucose uptake in cells. It plays a crucial role in maintaining energy balance and preventing hyperglycemia (high blood sugar).
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High insulin levels, often seen in insulin resistance, are associated with an increased risk of developing type 2 diabetes and metabolic syndrome. These conditions can lead to cardiovascular disease, kidney damage, and other complications[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11475114/)[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8907395/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low insulin levels can lead to hyperglycemia, which, if untreated, can cause diabetic ketoacidosis, a serious condition that requires immediate medical attention. Additionally, low insulin levels are associated with type 1 diabetes, where the body's immune system attacks the insulin-producing cells[6](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25541899/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Engage in regular physical activity to improve insulin sensitivity 
- Maintain a balanced diet low in refined carbohydrates and sugars 
- Manage weight to reduce body fat, which can improve insulin function 
- Get adequate sleep to support metabolic health 
- Reduce stress through relaxation techniques
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Sedentary lifestyle 
- High intake of processed foods and sugars 
- Obesity 
- Stress and lack of sleep 
- Certain medications and hormonal imbalances
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Insulin is secreted by pancreatic beta cells in response to elevated blood glucose levels. It binds to insulin receptors on target cells, initiating a cascade of signaling pathways that promote glucose uptake and storage. Insulin resistance, a hallmark of type 2 diabetes, occurs when these signaling pathways are impaired, leading to reduced glucose uptake and increased glucose production by the liver[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11475114/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3083884/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring insulin levels is important because it helps diagnose and manage diabetes, particularly type 2 diabetes, which is linked to insulin resistance. Insulin resistance occurs when the body's cells do not respond effectively to insulin, leading to elevated blood sugar levels. Early detection of insulin-related issues can prevent complications like cardiovascular disease and metabolic syndrome[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11475114/)[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4137169/).

biomarker.info.description: Alkaline Phosphatase (ALP) is an enzyme that catalyzes the hydrolysis of phosphate esters at alkaline pH, found in tissues like bone, liver, and intestine. It plays a role in bone calcification and phosphate transport
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High ALP levels are linked to conditions like liver disease, bone disorders, and some cancers. Elevated ALP can indicate bone metastasis or liver dysfunction, which are serious health risks[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4062654/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6784369/)[8](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10643954/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low ALP levels have been associated with poor prognosis in certain cancers, such as breast and colorectal cancer, possibly due to decreased cellular differentiation[8](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10643954/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a balanced diet rich in nutrients essential for bone health 
- Engage in regular physical activity to support bone density 
- Avoid excessive alcohol consumption, which can harm liver function 
- Ensure adequate vitamin D and calcium intake for bone health
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Excessive alcohol consumption 
- Poor diet lacking essential nutrients 
- Lack of physical activity 
- Certain medications that affect liver or bone health
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: ALP is a membrane-bound glycoprotein with four main isozymes: intestinal, placental, germ cell, and tissue nonspecific (liver/bone/kidney) ALP. It is involved in the hydrolysis of phosphate monoesters, which is crucial for bone calcification and cellular phosphate transport. ALP's role in disease is complex, with elevated levels often indicating tissue damage or disease progression, while decreased levels may suggest poor cellular differentiation in certain cancers[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4062654/)[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6351214/)[8](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10643954/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring ALP is important because it serves as a biomarker for various diseases, including bone disorders, liver dysfunction, and certain cancers. Elevated ALP levels can indicate conditions such as bone metastasis or liver disease, while low levels may be associated with poor prognosis in some cancers. It is a valuable tool in clinical diagnostics and research for monitoring disease progression and treatment outcomes[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4062654/)[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34719310/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6784369/).

biomarker.info.description: La ferritine est une protéine qui stocke le fer dans le corps. Elle est utilisée comme biomarqueur pour évaluer les niveaux de fer et l'inflammation. Une ferritine élevée peut indiquer une surcharge en fer ou une inflammation, tandis que des niveaux bas suggèrent une carence en fer.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: Des niveaux élevés de ferritine peuvent indiquer une surcharge en fer, ce qui peut conduire à des conditions telles que l'hémochromatose, des dommages au foie et un risque accru d'infections. Une ferritine élevée est également liée à l'inflammation et au stress oxydatif, contribuant aux dommages tissulaires et à de mauvais résultats dans les maladies critiques[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11061809/)[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9399505/)[8](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24549403/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Des niveaux bas de ferritine sont associés à une carence en fer, qui peut conduire à l'anémie, la fatigue, et à une fonction cognitive altérée. Une carence sévère peut affecter la fonction immunitaire et la santé globale[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10887646/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2717717/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintenir un régime équilibré avec un apport adéquat en fer 
- Éviter les suppléments de fer excessifs sauf avis médical 
- Gérer l'inflammation chronique par des changements de mode de vie et un traitement médical 
- Surveiller régulièrement les niveaux de ferritine dans les conditions associées au déséquilibre du fer
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Apport excessif de fer 
- Inflammation chronique 
- Certains médicaments qui affectent le métabolisme du fer 
- Mauvaises habitudes alimentaires menant à une carence en fer
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: La ferritine est une protéine de stockage du fer majeure qui joue un rôle crucial dans le maintien de l'homéostasie du fer. Elle est impliquée dans divers processus physiologiques et pathologiques, y compris l'inflammation et le stress oxydatif. En tant que réactif de phase aiguë, les niveaux de ferritine augmentent en réponse à l'inflammation, ce qui en fait un marqueur précieux pour des conditions telles que les infections et les maladies auto-immunes[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2717717/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2893236/)[7](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11763953/).
biomarker.info.importance: Mesurer la ferritine est important car cela aide à diagnostiquer et gérer les conditions liées à une carence ou une surcharge en fer, telles que l'anémie et l'hémochromatose. De plus, la ferritine est un marqueur inflammatoire, ce qui la rend utile pour évaluer la gravité de la maladie et prédire les résultats dans des conditions comme la COVID-19 et la septicémie[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8604557/)[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11061809/)[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9399505/).

biomarker.info.description: La protéine C-réactive (CRP) est une protéine de phase aiguë synthétisée par le foie en réponse à l'inflammation. Elle sert de biomarqueur pour diverses conditions inflammatoires, indiquant la présence d'une inflammation dans le corps et jouant un rôle dans la réponse immunitaire.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: Des niveaux élevés de CRP sont associés à un risque accru d'événements cardiovasculaires tels que des crises cardiaques ou des AVC en raison de son rôle dans la promotion de l'inflammation au sein des vaisseaux sanguins. Une élévation chronique peut également indiquer des infections en cours ou des maladies auto-immunes qui peuvent entraîner des dommages tissulaires au fil du temps.
biomarker.info.risksLow: Les faibles niveaux de CRP indiquent généralement une absence d'inflammation significative ; cependant, des niveaux extrêmement bas ou indétectables peuvent ne pas fournir suffisamment d'informations sur les problèmes de santé sous-jacents ou les réponses immunitaires.
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintenir une alimentation équilibrée riche en aliments anti-inflammatoires comme les fruits, les légumes, les noix 
- Participer à une activité physique régulière 
- Gérer le stress par des pratiques de pleine conscience 
- Éviter de fumer et limiter la consommation d'alcool 
- Contrôler le poids par des choix de mode de vie sains
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Mauvaise alimentation riche en aliments transformés 
- Style de vie sédentaire 
- Stress chronique 
- Tabagisme 
- Consommation excessive d'alcool
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: La CRP est produite par les hépatocytes sous la stimulation de cytokines pro-inflammatoires comme IL-6 et TNF-alpha pendant les réponses inflammatoires. Elle existe principalement sous deux formes : la CRP pentamérique (pCRP) qui agit comme un réactif de phase aiguë pendant l'inflammation, et la CRP monomérique (mCRP), qui a des activités biologiques distinctes incluant la promotion de la phagocytose et l'activation des voies du complément. Les tests haute sensibilité peuvent détecter de faibles niveaux de CRP qui corrèlent avec un risque cardiovasculaire accru en raison de son rôle dans le développement de l'athérosclérose. Des études ont montré que des niveaux élevés de CRP sont liés à diverses maladies, notamment des désordres neurodégénératifs comme la maladie d'Alzheimer, des cancers tels que le cancer du sein, et des conditions inflammatoires chroniques comme la polyarthrite rhumatoïde.
biomarker.info.importance: Mesurer les niveaux de CRP est crucial pour diagnostiquer et surveiller les maladies inflammatoires, les risques cardiovasculaires et les infections. Des niveaux élevés de CRP sont associés à des conditions chroniques telles que les maladies cardiaques, le diabète et les troubles auto-immuns. En suivant la CRP, les professionnels de santé peuvent évaluer la progression de la maladie et l'efficacité du traitement.

biomarker.info.description: Triglycerides are a type of fat found in the blood, often used as a biomarker for cardiovascular health. They are a key component of lipids (fats) and are crucial for energy storage and metabolism. Elevated levels can indicate increased risk of heart disease and other metabolic issues.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High triglyceride levels are associated with increased risk of cardiovascular diseases, pancreatitis, and metabolic syndrome. They can also be a marker for insulin resistance and type 2 diabetes[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33546998/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3234107/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low triglyceride levels are generally not associated with significant health risks, but they can occur in conditions like malnutrition or certain genetic disorders.
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a healthy diet low in saturated fats and added sugars 
- Engage in regular physical activity to improve lipid profiles 
- Manage weight to reduce metabolic risks 
- Limit alcohol consumption 
- Consider omega-3 fatty acid supplements under medical guidance
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- High intake of saturated fats and trans fats 
- Consuming large amounts of alcohol 
- Obesity and lack of physical activity 
- Certain medications (e.g., steroids, beta-blockers) 
- High sugar intake
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Triglycerides are a major form of fat in the body and play a significant role in lipid metabolism. They are transported in the bloodstream by lipoproteins, such as very-low-density lipoproteins (VLDL). High triglyceride levels can indicate the presence of atherogenic lipoproteins, which contribute to the development of atherosclerosis (the buildup of plaque in arteries) and increase the risk of cardiovascular events[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3234107/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5695560/). The triglyceride-glucose index (TyG index), which combines triglyceride and glucose levels, is used as a biomarker for insulin resistance and metabolic syndrome[1](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39510865/)[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11063788/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring triglycerides is important because high levels are associated with increased risk of cardiovascular diseases, including heart attacks and strokes. Triglycerides are also linked to metabolic syndrome, diabetes, and other health conditions. Monitoring triglyceride levels helps in early detection and management of these conditions, making it a vital tool in preventive healthcare[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33546998/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3234107/).

biomarker.info.description: The HOMA index, specifically HOMA-IR (Homeostasis Model Assessment for Insulin Resistance), is a biomarker used to assess insulin resistance (IR), a condition where the body's cells do not respond effectively to insulin, leading to high blood sugar levels. It is calculated using fasting insulin and glucose levels
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High HOMA-IR values indicate insulin resistance, which is linked to an increased risk of developing type 2 diabetes, metabolic syndrome, cardiovascular diseases, and non-alcoholic fatty liver disease[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10652621/)[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10590044/)[4](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28746378/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low HOMA-IR values typically indicate good insulin sensitivity, which is generally not associated with significant health risks. However, extremely low values might suggest other metabolic issues, but this is less common and not well-documented.
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Engage in regular physical activity to improve insulin sensitivity 
- Maintain a healthy weight through diet and exercise 
- Follow a balanced diet low in refined carbohydrates and saturated fats 
- Increase consumption of fiber-rich foods and omega-3 fatty acids 
- Manage stress levels
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Sedentary lifestyle 
- High intake of processed foods and sugars 
- Obesity 
- Lack of sleep 
- Certain medications (e.g., steroids) 
- Stress
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: HOMA-IR is calculated as the product of fasting insulin (in mU/L) and fasting glucose (in mmol/L) divided by 22.5. It provides a convenient and cost-effective method to estimate insulin resistance compared to more invasive techniques like the hyperinsulinemic euglycemic clamp. Insulin resistance is a key factor in the pathogenesis of T2DM and MetS, leading to hyperinsulinemia and potentially β-cell failure[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6571793/)[8](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11475114/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring HOMA-IR is important because it helps identify individuals at risk of developing type 2 diabetes (T2DM) and metabolic syndrome (MetS), conditions associated with insulin resistance. Early detection allows for timely interventions to prevent or manage these diseases. HOMA-IR is also a useful tool in assessing the risk of non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD) in non-diabetic populations[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10652621/)[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10590044/)[4](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28746378/).

biomarker.info.description: Vitamin B9, or folate, is crucial for nucleic acid biosynthesis, DNA repair, and methylation. It acts as a cofactor in various biological processes, including the synthesis of purines and pyrimidines, and is essential for cell division and growth, particularly during pregnancy
biomarker.info.risksHigh: Excessive intake of synthetic folate (folic acid) may increase the risk of carcinogenesis, disrupt DNA methylation, and impact embryogenesis and neurodevelopment[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37960352/)
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low levels of Vitamin B9 are associated with megaloblastic anemia, hyperhomocysteinemia, cardiovascular diseases, neural tube defects, and cognitive impairments[3](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24298825/)[8](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31280597/)
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Consume folate-rich foods like leafy greens and legumes 
- Maintain adequate vitamin B12 levels to support folate metabolism 
- Consider supplements if necessary, especially during pregnancy 
- Ensure balanced intake to avoid excessive levels of synthetic folic acid
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Poor dietary intake 
- Environmental and hereditary factors 
- Aging 
- Excessive intake of synthetic folic acid 
- Lack of vitamin B12
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Vitamin B9 is essential for the one-carbon cycle, which is vital for DNA synthesis and repair. The biologically active forms, reduced tetrahydrofolates, serve as cofactors in methylation reactions and the synthesis of purines and pyrimidines. Folate also supports the immune system by aiding the survival of regulatory T cells[1](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30228213/)[3](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24298825/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3282783/). Its deficiency can lead to hyperhomocysteinemia, a risk factor for cardiovascular diseases[3](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24298825/)
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring Vitamin B9 is important because it plays a pivotal role in DNA synthesis, repair, and methylation, impacting health and disease. Folate deficiency is linked to conditions like megaloblastic anemia, cardiovascular diseases, and neural tube defects, while excessive intake may lead to carcinogenesis and epigenetic changes[1](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30228213/)[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37960352/)[3](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24298825/). Monitoring folate levels helps in managing these risks and ensuring optimal health outcomes

biomarker.info.description: Thyroid-Stimulating Hormone (TSH) is a hormone produced by the pituitary gland that regulates the production of thyroid hormones (thyroxine [T4] and triiodothyronine [T3]) by the thyroid gland. It acts as a feedback mechanism to ensure proper thyroid function
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High TSH levels indicate hypothyroidism, which can cause fatigue, weight gain, and cold intolerance. Untreated hypothyroidism may lead to complications such as cardiovascular disease and cognitive impairment[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6778876/)[7](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10726078/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low TSH levels are often associated with hyperthyroidism, which can lead to symptoms like weight loss, anxiety, and increased heart rate. Untreated hyperthyroidism can result in serious health issues, including heart problems and osteoporosis[7](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10726078/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a balanced diet rich in iodine (e.g., seafood, iodized salt) 
- Avoid excessive intake of goitrogens (e.g., soy, cruciferous vegetables) 
- Ensure adequate selenium intake (e.g., Brazil nuts) 
- Manage stress levels 
- Regular exercise to improve overall health
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Iodine deficiency 
- Excessive intake of goitrogens 
- Certain medications (e.g., lithium) 
- Stress 
- Smoking 
- Lack of selenium
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: TSH is the most sensitive marker for evaluating thyroid function due to its log-linear relationship with free thyroxine (fT4). It is used to diagnose primary thyroid disease and monitor treatment efficacy. TSH levels are influenced by various factors, including age, smoking, and the presence of autoantibodies[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10517335/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6778876/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3529417/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring TSH is crucial for diagnosing and managing thyroid disorders, such as hypothyroidism and hyperthyroidism. It is the primary biomarker for evaluating thyroid function and guiding treatment, making it essential for maintaining metabolic health and preventing complications associated with thyroid dysfunction[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5321289/)[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10517335/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6778876/).

biomarker.info.description: Albumin is a crucial protein in the blood, primarily synthesized by the liver, responsible for maintaining blood volume and pressure, transporting various substances like hormones and drugs, and acting as an antioxidant. It is a key indicator of nutritional status and liver function.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High albumin levels are not typically associated with significant health risks but may reflect dehydration or other transient conditions. However, there is limited literature on the adverse effects of elevated albumin levels.
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low albumin levels (hypoalbuminemia) are linked to increased mortality risk, poor surgical outcomes, reduced muscle mass, and impaired immunity. It is a marker of malnutrition and liver dysfunction[7](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11664120/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a balanced diet rich in protein 
- Ensure adequate hydration 
- Manage liver health through appropriate medical care 
- Address malnutrition if present
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Liver diseases 
- Malnutrition 
- Chronic inflammation 
- Dehydration 
- Certain medications
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Albumin is the most abundant protein in blood plasma, with a molecular mass of about 66 kDa. It consists of three homologous domains and plays a critical role in maintaining plasma oncotic pressure and transporting ligands. Albumin is a negative acute-phase reactant, meaning its levels decrease in response to inflammation[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10532125/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8967674/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring albumin is important because it serves as a prognostic indicator in various clinical conditions, including liver diseases, malabsorption syndromes, cardiovascular diseases, and cancer. Low albumin levels are associated with increased mortality risk and poor outcomes in several diseases[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10532125/)[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37762957/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11267779/).

biomarker.info.description: Potassium is an essential mineral and electrolyte that plays a critical role in various bodily functions, including muscle contraction, nerve transmission, and maintaining fluid balance. It helps regulate blood pressure and supports cardiovascular health by counteracting sodium's effects.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High levels of potassium (hyperkalemia) pose risks including potentially life-threatening cardiac arrhythmias or arrest due to its effect on myocardial excitability. It may also indicate severe underlying conditions like renal failure or adrenal insufficiency.
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low levels of potassium (hypokalemia) can lead to serious complications such as muscle weakness, cramping, fatigue, irregular heart rhythms (arrhythmias), increased risk of high blood pressure, kidney stones, and impaired glucose tolerance.
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Consume foods rich in potassium such as bananas, oranges, potatoes, spinach, beans 
- Stay hydrated to support kidney function 
- Limit sodium intake which competes with potassium 
- Engage in regular physical activity which promotes healthy metabolism 
- Monitor medications that may affect serum potassium levels.
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- High sodium diets 
- Excessive alcohol consumption 
- Certain medications like diuretics that increase urinary loss of potassium 
- Chronic diarrhea or vomiting leading to electrolyte imbalances 
- Inadequate dietary intake due to restrictive diets.
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Potassium acts as a key regulator of cellular functions by maintaining the resting membrane potential in cells, which is crucial for nerve impulse transmission and muscle contractions. The body tightly regulates plasma potassium levels through renal excretion mechanisms to maintain homeostasis. Potassium influences vascular smooth muscle tone; adequate levels promote vasodilation (widening of blood vessels), thereby lowering blood pressure. Additionally, it plays a role in metabolic processes such as protein synthesis and carbohydrate metabolism. Deficiencies or excesses can lead to significant clinical consequences: hypokalemia (low potassium) may cause weakness or arrhythmias while hyperkalemia (high potassium) can result in cardiac arrest if not managed promptly.
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring potassium levels is vital for assessing overall health, particularly cardiovascular function. Abnormal potassium levels can indicate underlying health issues such as kidney disease or hormonal imbalances. Monitoring potassium intake can help prevent hypertension (high blood pressure) and reduce the risk of stroke and heart disease.

biomarker.info.description: Conjugated bilirubin is a water-soluble form of bilirubin, produced when unconjugated bilirubin is processed by the liver. It plays a role in detoxification and acts as an antioxidant, helping protect against oxidative stress and lipid peroxidation
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High levels of conjugated bilirubin can indicate liver dysfunction, bile duct obstruction, or other liver diseases, leading to jaundice and potentially severe health complications[8](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11637320/)
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low levels of conjugated bilirubin are not typically associated with specific health risks but may indicate efficient liver function or low bilirubin production
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a healthy diet rich in fruits and vegetables 
- Stay hydrated to support liver function 
- Avoid excessive alcohol consumption 
- Engage in regular physical activity to improve overall health 
- Manage stress levels
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Excessive alcohol consumption 
- Poor diet lacking essential nutrients 
- Obesity and sedentary lifestyle 
- Certain medications that can harm the liver 
- Environmental toxins
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Conjugated bilirubin is formed in the liver through the conjugation of unconjugated bilirubin with glucuronic acid, making it water-soluble and facilitating its excretion into bile. This process is energy-dependent and crucial for the removal of bilirubin from the body. Conjugated bilirubin acts as an antioxidant, preventing lipid peroxidation and contributing to detoxification processes in the body[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10197288/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC299492/). Its levels are indicative of liver function and can be used to diagnose conditions like jaundice[8](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11637320/)
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring conjugated bilirubin is important because it helps diagnose liver dysfunction and jaundice. Elevated levels can indicate issues with bilirubin excretion, such as liver disease or bile duct obstruction. Conjugated bilirubin also has antioxidant properties, which can protect against oxidative damage[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10197288/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC299492/). Monitoring its levels aids in assessing liver health and managing related conditions

biomarker.info.description: Total bilirubin is a biomarker that measures the sum of conjugated (direct) and unconjugated (indirect) bilirubin in the blood. It is a product of hemoglobin breakdown and is primarily processed by the liver. Elevated levels can indicate liver dysfunction or other health issues.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High bilirubin levels can indicate liver dysfunction, jaundice, or other serious health conditions. Elevated levels are associated with increased risks of liver diseases, such as cirrhosis and hepatitis, and may also be linked to cardiovascular and other oxidative stress-related conditions[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10197288/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5655285/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low bilirubin levels are generally not associated with significant health risks but may indicate conditions such as Gilbert's syndrome, which is usually benign. However, very low levels might be linked to certain oxidative stress conditions where bilirubin's antioxidant properties are beneficial[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5655285/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a healthy diet rich in fruits and vegetables 
- Stay hydrated to support liver function 
- Avoid excessive alcohol consumption 
- Engage in regular physical activity to improve overall health 
- Manage stress levels
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Excessive alcohol consumption 
- Poor diet lacking essential nutrients 
- Obesity and lack of physical activity 
- Certain medications that can affect liver function 
- Environmental toxins
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Total bilirubin is produced from the breakdown of hemoglobin, primarily in the spleen and bone marrow. It exists in two forms: unconjugated (lipid-soluble) and conjugated (water-soluble). Unconjugated bilirubin is transported to the liver bound to albumin, where it is converted to conjugated bilirubin by the enzyme uridine diphosphate-glucuronosyltransferase (UGT1A1). This process is crucial for bilirubin excretion. Bilirubin levels provide insights into liver function, disease severity, and prognosis in liver diseases[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4113062/)[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11557368/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring total bilirubin is important because it serves as a key indicator of liver function and health. It helps in diagnosing liver diseases such as hepatitis and cirrhosis, and it is also linked to oxidative stress and inflammation levels in the body. Monitoring bilirubin levels aids in the early detection and management of liver conditions and other diseases associated with oxidative stress[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10197288/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5655285/).

biomarker.info.description: Le sodium est un cation extracellulaire crucial essentiel pour maintenir l'équilibre hydrique, la fonction nerveuse et la contraction musculaire. Il est souvent mesuré par des biomarqueurs urinaires pour évaluer les niveaux d'apport.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: Un apport élevé en sodium est associé à une augmentation de la pression artérielle, des maladies cardiovasculaires et du risque d'AVC. Cela peut également aggraver des conditions comme la maladie rénale[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8468043/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10845896/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Des niveaux bas de sodium (hyponatrémie) peuvent entraîner des symptômes neurologiques, une faiblesse musculaire et dans les cas graves, des crises ou un coma. Elle est souvent associée à des conditions telles que l'insuffisance cardiaque ou les maladies du foie[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8468043/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Consommer le sodium avec modération, idéalement en dessous de 2 300 mg par jour 
- Utiliser des herbes et des épices pour assaisonner les aliments au lieu du sel 
- Choisir des options pauvres en sodium lorsque disponible 
- Surveiller les niveaux de sodium urinaire pour une évaluation précise de l'apport
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Aliments riches en sodium (par ex., viandes transformées, conserves) 
- Usage excessif de sel de table 
- Manque d'apport en potassium, ce qui peut exacerber les effets du sodium sur la pression artérielle
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Le sodium joue un rôle vital dans les processus physiologiques, y compris le maintien du volume et de l'osmolalité extracellulaires, des potentiels de membrane et du transport transmembranaire. Son apport est étroitement régulé par les processus rénaux, biochimiques, endocriniens, immunitaires et neuronaux pour maintenir le sodium sanguin dans une plage normale[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5666762/)[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8468043/). Les biomarqueurs urinaires, en particulier les collectes d'urine de 24 heures, sont utilisés pour estimer avec précision l'apport en sodium[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5497310/).
biomarker.info.importance: Mesurer l'apport en sodium est important car il est lié à la régulation de la pression artérielle et à la santé cardiovasculaire. Un apport élevé en sodium peut augmenter la pression artérielle, un facteur de risque majeur pour les maladies cardiaques et les AVC. Surveiller les niveaux de sodium aide à gérer ces conditions et à comprendre l'impact du sodium alimentaire sur les résultats de santé[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8468043/)[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3771149/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10845896/).

biomarker.info.description: Les lipases sont des enzymes qui décomposent les graisses (triglycérides) en glycérol et acides gras. Elles sont cruciales pour la digestion et le métabolisme. Dans le contexte de la santé, les lipases, en particulier la lipase pancréatique, servent de biomarqueurs pour des conditions comme la pancréatite aiguë.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: Des niveaux élevés de lipase sont principalement associés à la pancréatite aiguë, qui peut entraîner de graves complications si elle n'est pas traitée rapidement. Des niveaux élevés de lipase peuvent également indiquer d'autres troubles pancréatiques[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4541003/)[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4299384/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Des niveaux bas de lipase ne sont généralement pas associés à des risques de santé significatifs mais peuvent indiquer des problèmes de malabsorption si la fonction pancréatique est altérée.
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintenir un régime équilibré pour soutenir la santé pancréatique 
- Éviter la consommation excessive d'alcool, qui peut conduire à la pancréatite 
- Gérer les conditions comme l'hypertriglycéridémie pour prévenir le stress pancréatique 
- Rester hydraté pour soutenir la santé digestive globale
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Consommation excessive d'alcool 
- Régimes riches en graisses qui peuvent solliciter la fonction pancréatique 
- Certains médicaments comme le furosémide, qui peuvent augmenter l'activité de la lipase 
- Hypertriglycéridémie
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Les lipases, en particulier la lipase pancréatique, sont des enzymes clés dans le diagnostic de la pancréatite aiguë. Elles sont plus sensibles et spécifiques que l'amylase, une autre enzyme utilisée à cet effet. La lipase pancréatique est sécrétée par le pancréas et joue un rôle crucial dans la digestion des graisses. Ses niveaux augmentent significativement dans la pancréatite aiguë, en faisant un marqueur de diagnostic précieux. Contrairement à l'amylase, la lipase n'est pas affectée par l'hypertriglycéridémie et reste élevée plus longtemps, aidant dans les diagnostics tardifs[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4541003/)[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15943725/)[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4299384/).
biomarker.info.importance: Mesurer les niveaux de lipase est important car elles sont des marqueurs sensibles et spécifiques pour la pancréatite aiguë, une condition où le pancréas s'enflamme. Les niveaux de lipase augmentent dans les heures suivant le début de la pancréatite et demeurent élevés pendant plusieurs jours, ce qui en fait un outil de diagnostic fiable par rapport à d'autres enzymes comme l'amylase[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4541003/)[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15943725/).

biomarker.info.description: Uric acid is a biomarker produced during the breakdown of purines, which are compounds found in many foods and naturally in the body. It acts as an antioxidant (a substance that prevents damage from free radicals) at moderate levels but can cause health issues like gout (a type of arthritis) and kidney problems when elevated
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High uric acid levels are associated with increased mortality risk, particularly in type 2 diabetes patients. Hyperuricemia is linked to cardiovascular and renal complications, and it plays an independent role in these diseases[4](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18585721/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8801359/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low uric acid levels (hypouricemia) can lead to health issues such as hereditary renal hypouricemia, which may cause exercise-induced acute kidney injury.
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a balanced diet low in purines 
- Stay hydrated to help kidneys flush out uric acid 
- Exercise regularly to improve overall metabolic health 
- Limit alcohol consumption, especially beer 
- Avoid sugary drinks and foods high in fructose
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- High-purine foods (e.g., red meat, seafood) 
- Alcohol consumption 
- Sugary drinks and foods high in fructose 
- Obesity and lack of physical activity 
- Certain medications (e.g., diuretics)
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Uric acid is the end product of purine metabolism. It plays a dual role in health, acting as an antioxidant at moderate levels but contributing to disease when elevated. Hyperuricemia is linked to cardiovascular and metabolic disorders, and its levels are influenced by diet, genetics, and environmental factors. Uric acid is a predictor of cardiovascular outcomes, especially in patients undergoing procedures like percutaneous coronary intervention. It is also recognized for its role in oxidative stress and as a potential biomarker for neurodegenerative diseases[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7065265/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8801359/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4062324/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring uric acid is crucial because its levels are linked to various health conditions. Elevated uric acid (hyperuricemia) is associated with gout and a range of comorbidities, including cardiovascular diseases, chronic kidney disease, and diabetes. Monitoring uric acid helps in early detection and management of these conditions, making it a vital tool in preventive healthcare. It is also implicated in neurodegenerative diseases like Parkinson's disease and serves as a marker for increased cardiovascular risk[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7065265/)[4](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18585721/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4062324/).

biomarker.info.description: Gamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT) is an enzyme involved in the transfer of gamma-glutamyl groups, playing a key role in antioxidant defense mechanisms, particularly in glutathione recycling. It is a marker for liver health and oxidative stress
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High GGT levels are linked to increased risks of cardiovascular diseases, metabolic syndrome, liver diseases, and certain cancers. Elevated GGT is also associated with higher mortality rates and poorer survival in cancer patients[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4620378/)[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20021625/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3341856/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low GGT levels are generally not associated with significant health risks, but they may indicate reduced antioxidant capacity or less oxidative stress[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11165564/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a balanced diet with antioxidants 
- Limit alcohol consumption 
- Engage in regular physical activity to reduce oxidative stress 
- Manage weight to reduce metabolic syndrome risk 
- Avoid exposure to heavy metals and environmental toxins
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Alcohol consumption 
- Obesity and sedentary lifestyle 
- Heavy metal exposure 
- High-fat diets contributing to liver stress 
- Certain medications that can elevate liver enzymes
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: GGT is a membrane-bound enzyme that catalyzes the transfer of gamma-glutamyl groups, contributing to glutathione metabolism and antioxidant defense. It is involved in the gamma-glutamyl cycle, which recycles glutathione, a major antioxidant in cells. GGT is expressed in various tissues, including the liver, kidneys, and pancreas, and its levels can reflect oxidative stress and liver damage[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11165564/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3341856/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring GGT is important because it serves as a predictive biomarker for various diseases, including liver diseases, cardiovascular conditions, diabetes, and certain cancers. Elevated GGT levels are associated with increased risks of metabolic syndrome, cardiovascular events, and all-cause mortality[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4620378/)[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20021625/)[3](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37519590/).

biomarker.info.description: Creatinine is a waste product from the normal breakdown of muscle tissue (creatine), which is filtered out by the kidneys. It serves as a key indicator of kidney function, particularly in assessing the glomerular filtration rate (GFR), which measures how well the kidneys are filtering waste from the blood
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High creatinine levels indicate impaired kidney function, which can lead to complications such as fluid buildup, electrolyte imbalances, and increased risk of cardiovascular diseases. Elevated creatinine is a marker of kidney disease progression and requires medical attention[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11512660/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5136473/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low creatinine levels are generally not associated with significant health risks but may reflect reduced muscle mass or other non-kidney related factors[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3686906/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a balanced diet to support overall health 
- Stay hydrated to help kidneys function properly 
- Avoid excessive protein intake, which can increase creatinine production 
- Limit exposure to nephrotoxic substances 
- Regular exercise can help maintain muscle mass and overall health
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Certain medications (e.g., cimetidine, trimethoprim) that inhibit creatinine secretion 
- Muscle diseases or malnutrition affecting muscle mass 
- High-protein diets increasing creatinine production 
- Dehydration reducing urine output and concentrating creatinine 
- Nephrotoxic substances
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Creatinine is produced from the non-enzymatic breakdown of creatine in muscle and is freely filtered by the glomerulus. However, it is not metabolized by the kidneys and can be secreted by the proximal tubules, which can lead to overestimation of GFR in certain conditions. Factors like muscle mass, age, and sex can influence creatinine levels, although serum cystatin C is considered more reliable in some cases due to its independence from these factors[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3686906/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5136473/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring creatinine is important because it helps assess kidney function and diagnose conditions like acute kidney injury (AKI) and chronic kidney disease (CKD). It is crucial for monitoring disease progression and guiding treatment decisions. Creatinine levels are used to calculate the estimated GFR (eGFR), which is essential for evaluating kidney health and managing related complications[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3686906/)[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11512660/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5136473/).

biomarker.info.description: Alanine Transaminase (ALT) is an enzyme found primarily in the liver, involved in the metabolism of amino acids. It is used as a biomarker for liver health, indicating liver damage when elevated in the blood.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: Elevated ALT levels are indicative of liver damage and may be associated with conditions like NAFLD, hepatitis, and cirrhosis. High ALT levels also predict increased risk of cardiovascular diseases and type 2 diabetes[8](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16682043/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Extremely low ALT levels may be associated with aging and frailty in older adults, though this requires further investigation[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4081315/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a healthy diet to reduce liver strain 
- Limit alcohol consumption 
- Avoid excessive use of certain medications known to affect liver health 
- Engage in regular physical activity to improve metabolic health
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Excessive alcohol consumption 
- Certain medications (e.g., statins, acetaminophen) 
- Viral infections (e.g., hepatitis) 
- Obesity and metabolic syndrome 
- Muscle injuries or diseases
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: ALT catalyzes the transamination of alanine and 2-oxoglutarate to form pyruvate and glutamate, playing a key role in glucose and protein metabolism[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2917112/). It is predominantly found in hepatocytes and is released into the bloodstream upon liver injury, making it a reliable indicator of liver damage[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10529728/). ALT levels can be influenced by factors such as viral infections, alcohol consumption, and certain medications[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4081315/)[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2917112/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring ALT is important because it helps diagnose and monitor liver diseases such as hepatitis and cirrhosis. It is also a marker for non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD) and can predict cardiovascular diseases and type 2 diabetes[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4081315/)[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25013373/)[8](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16682043/). ALT levels are crucial for assessing overall health, especially in conditions like obesity and metabolic syndrome[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10529728/).

biomarker.info.description: Vitamin B12 (cobalamin) is a crucial biomarker that measures the status of this essential micronutrient in the body. It is vital for DNA synthesis, nerve function, and red blood cell formation. Vitamin B12 deficiency can lead to conditions like anemia and neurological disorders
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High levels of Vitamin B12 are generally not harmful but may indicate excessive intake or other underlying conditions. However, there is limited evidence on the risks associated with elevated Vitamin B12 levels[5](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39367523/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low Vitamin B12 levels are associated with megaloblastic anemia, neurological disorders, and impaired cognitive function. Deficiency can also affect growth and development in children[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9651173/)[7](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9959711/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Consume foods rich in Vitamin B12, such as meat, fish, and dairy products 
- Consider supplements if dietary intake is insufficient, especially for vegetarians and vegans 
- Ensure adequate absorption by maintaining a healthy digestive system
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Vegetarian or vegan diet without supplementation 
- Poor absorption due to gastrointestinal disorders (e.g., celiac disease, Crohn's disease) 
- Certain medications (e.g., proton pump inhibitors) 
- Aging, as absorption efficiency decreases with age
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Vitamin B12 status is assessed through several biomarkers. **Serum B12** measures total circulating Vitamin B12, while **holotranscobalamin (holoTC)** reflects the biologically active fraction bound to transcobalamin, which is more indicative of the body's ability to utilize Vitamin B12[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4921487/)[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38987873/). **Methylmalonic acid (MMA)** and **homocysteine (Hcy)** are metabolic markers that accumulate when Vitamin B12 is insufficient, indicating functional deficiency[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3127527/)[5](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39367523/). These biomarkers provide a comprehensive view of Vitamin B12 status, from direct measurement to functional impact
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring Vitamin B12 is important because its deficiency can lead to serious health issues such as megaloblastic anemia, neuropathy, and neuropsychiatric changes. Early detection and treatment of Vitamin B12 deficiency are crucial to prevent these complications. Biomarkers like serum B12, holotranscobalamin (holoTC), methylmalonic acid (MMA), and homocysteine (Hcy) help in diagnosing and managing Vitamin B12 status effectively[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38987873/)[5](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39367523/)[8](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11707970/).

biomarker.info.description: LDL-Cholesterol (LDL-C) is a type of cholesterol found in the blood, often referred to as 'bad' cholesterol. It plays a crucial role in the development of atherosclerosis (the buildup of plaque in arteries), which can lead to cardiovascular diseases
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High levels of LDL-C increase the risk of atherosclerosis, heart attacks, and strokes. Elevated LDL-C is linked to metabolic syndrome, which includes conditions like hypertension, diabetes, and obesity[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11052465/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low levels of LDL-C are generally not associated with significant health risks, but very low levels might be seen in conditions like malnutrition or certain genetic disorders.
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a diet low in saturated fats and cholesterol 
- Increase intake of soluble fiber (e.g., oats, fruits) 
- Engage in regular physical activity 
- Manage weight to reduce obesity-related risks 
- Consider statin therapy under medical supervision
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- High intake of saturated fats and dietary cholesterol 
- Lack of physical activity 
- Obesity 
- Smoking 
- Certain medications (e.g., steroids)
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: LDL-C is a key component in the development and progression of atherosclerosis. It consists of several subclasses, with small dense LDL (sdLDL) being particularly atherogenic due to its susceptibility to modifications like oxidation and glycation, which enhance its role in inflammation and plaque formation[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5441126/)[5](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38969749/). The cumulative exposure to LDL over time significantly influences the risk of atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease (ASCVD), making long-term management crucial[5](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38969749/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring LDL-C is important because it is a major risk factor for cardiovascular disease (CVD). High levels of LDL-C are associated with increased risk of atherosclerosis and acute coronary syndromes. Monitoring LDL-C helps in assessing the risk of heart disease and in managing treatments like statins to reduce this risk[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3190417/)[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11052465/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10037190/).

biomarker.info.description: Mean Cell Volume (MCV) is a measure of the average size of red blood cells (RBCs), which are crucial for delivering oxygen throughout the body. It helps diagnose various types of anemia and other health conditions by indicating whether RBCs are smaller (microcytic), normal (normocytic), or larger (macrocytic) than usual
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High MCV levels are linked to macrocytic anemia, which can result from vitamin B12 or folate deficiency, alcohol abuse, or liver disease. Elevated MCV is also associated with increased mortality risks in certain clinical settings, such as chronic kidney disease and cardiovascular diseases[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7392927/)[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9463929/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low MCV levels are associated with microcytic anemia, which can lead to fatigue, weakness, and shortness of breath. Common causes include iron deficiency, thalassemia, and chronic inflammation[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3610441/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Ensure adequate intake of vitamin B12 and folate through diet or supplements 
- Limit alcohol consumption 
- Maintain a balanced diet rich in iron (for those with low MCV) 
- Address underlying conditions like liver disease or hypothyroidism
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Alcohol abuse 
- Vitamin B12 or folate deficiency 
- Liver disease 
- Hypothyroidism 
- Poor dietary intake of essential nutrients
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: MCV is a critical hematological parameter used to classify anemias based on RBC size. It is calculated from a complete blood count (CBC) and is essential for identifying microcytic (low MCV), normocytic (normal MCV), and macrocytic (high MCV) anemias. Macrocytic anemia, often indicated by an elevated MCV, can result from vitamin B12 or folate deficiency, alcohol abuse, or liver disease. Conversely, a low MCV suggests microcytic anemia, commonly seen in iron deficiency or thalassemia[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9463929/)[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3610441/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring MCV is important because it aids in diagnosing and managing conditions like anemia, which can be caused by iron deficiency, vitamin B12 or folate deficiency, or other factors. Elevated MCV levels are associated with increased mortality risks in certain clinical settings, such as chronic kidney disease and cardiovascular diseases. It also helps in assessing the prognosis of various health conditions, including malignancies and liver diseases[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7392927/)[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9463929/)[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3610441/).

biomarker.info.description: Estimated Glomerular Filtration Rate (eGFR) is a biomarker that measures kidney function by estimating the rate at which the kidneys filter waste from the blood. It is crucial for assessing the health of the kidneys and diagnosing conditions like chronic kidney disease (CKD).
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High eGFR values are less commonly associated with health risks but may indicate overestimation due to factors like muscle mass or certain medications. However, high eGFR is not typically a concern in clinical practice[7](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11262368/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low eGFR levels indicate impaired kidney function, which can lead to complications such as fluid buildup, electrolyte imbalances, and increased risk of cardiovascular diseases and mortality[7](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11262368/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a healthy diet low in sodium and protein 
- Stay hydrated to support kidney function 
- Exercise regularly to improve overall health 
- Manage blood pressure and diabetes through lifestyle changes and medication if necessary 
- Avoid smoking and excessive alcohol consumption
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- High blood pressure 
- Diabetes 
- Obesity 
- Smoking 
- Excessive alcohol consumption 
- Certain medications (e.g., NSAIDs) 
- Family history of kidney disease
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: eGFR is calculated using formulas like the CKD-EPI equation, which incorporates variables such as age, sex, race, and serum creatinine levels. It reflects the sum of the filtration rates of all functioning nephrons in the kidneys. eGFR serves as a prognostic marker for cardiovascular events and mortality, and it is essential for therapeutic decisions in patients with CKD[7](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11262368/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring eGFR is important because it helps diagnose and monitor chronic kidney disease, predict cardiovascular events, and determine the risk of end-stage kidney disease (ESKD) and mortality. It is also used to adjust medication dosages and monitor treatment effects in clinical settings[7](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11262368/).

biomarker.info.description: Magnesium is a crucial mineral involved in numerous physiological processes, including enzyme activity, energy production, and neuromuscular function. It serves as a cofactor for many enzymes and is essential for maintaining cellular integrity and overall health.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High magnesium levels (hypermagnesemia) are less common but can pose serious risks, especially in individuals with impaired renal function or those receiving high doses of magnesium supplements[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11444808/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low magnesium levels (hypomagnesemia) can lead to neuromuscular symptoms, cardiovascular issues, and metabolic complications. It is particularly risky for individuals with chronic illnesses or those experiencing malnutrition[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11444808/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Include magnesium-rich foods in your diet, such as dark leafy greens, nuts, and whole grains 
- Consider magnesium supplements if dietary intake is insufficient 
- Maintain adequate hydration to support magnesium absorption 
- Limit alcohol consumption, which can impair magnesium absorption
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Poor dietary intake 
- Chronic illnesses 
- Malnutrition 
- Impaired renal function 
- Excessive alcohol consumption 
- Certain medications that interfere with magnesium absorption
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Magnesium is vital for various biochemical processes, including those related to energy metabolism and neuromuscular function. However, diagnosing magnesium status can be challenging due to its compartmentalization in the body. Biomarkers like Na/K ATPase, thromboxane B2, C-reactive protein, and endothelin-1 have been proposed to better reflect magnesium's role in biochemical processes[1](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15637224/)[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6163803/). Ionized magnesium is considered a more accurate measure of bioavailability compared to total magnesium[8](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8370522/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring magnesium is important because it helps assess nutritional status and diagnose deficiencies, which are common among populations with chronic illnesses or malnutrition. Magnesium plays a significant role in cardiovascular health, and its levels can influence disease prognosis and management[1](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15637224/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11444808/).

biomarker.info.description: Mean Platelet Volume (MPV) is a measure of the average size of platelets in the blood. It reflects platelet activity and is used as a biomarker for various health conditions, including cardiovascular diseases and inflammatory processes
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High MPV levels are associated with increased risks of cardiovascular diseases, such as myocardial infarction and stroke, as well as other conditions like diabetes and certain cancers[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31148950/)[7](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10909253/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low MPV levels have been observed in conditions like tuberculosis during disease exacerbation and certain neoplastic diseases, suggesting reduced platelet activity or production[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31148950/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a healthy lifestyle to reduce inflammation and cardiovascular risk 
- Avoid smoking and excessive alcohol consumption 
- Engage in regular physical activity to improve cardiovascular health 
- Manage stress levels
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Smoking 
- Excessive alcohol consumption 
- Poor diet 
- Lack of physical activity 
- Stress 
- Certain medications
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: MPV is calculated during routine blood tests and reflects the size of platelets, which are essential for blood clotting and inflammation. Larger platelets are more active and contain more prothrombotic material, making them more likely to aggregate and form clots[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5094934/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3739454/). MPV is inversely related to platelet count under normal conditions but can be altered in various pathologies, indicating changes in platelet production or activation[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6501263/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring MPV is important because it provides insights into platelet activity, which is crucial for understanding the risk and prognosis of cardiovascular events, inflammatory diseases, and certain cancers. MPV can serve as a predictive and prognostic biomarker, helping in early detection and management of these conditions[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6501263/)[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31148950/).

biomarker.info.description: La progestérone est une hormone stéroïde cruciale pour le maintien de la grossesse et la régulation du cycle menstruel. Elle se lie aux récepteurs de la progestérone (PR), influençant diverses fonctions corporelles, y compris les réponses immunitaires et la croissance cellulaire.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: Des niveaux élevés de progestérone ne sont généralement pas nocifs mais peuvent être associés à certaines conditions comme l'hyperprolactinémie ou le syndrome des ovaires polykystiques (SOPK) dans certains contextes. Cependant, les risques sont plus liés à l'équilibre de la progestérone qu'à ses niveaux absolus.
biomarker.info.risksLow: Les faibles niveaux de progestérone sont associés à des risques accrus d'accouchement prématuré et d'échec précoce de la grossesse. Chez les femmes non enceintes, une faible progestérone peut perturber les cycles menstruels et la fertilité.
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintenir un poids sain pour soutenir l'équilibre hormonal 
- Participer à une activité physique régulière pour améliorer la santé globale 
- Assurer un sommeil adéquat et une gestion du stress 
- Envisager des suppléments alimentaires comme la vitamine D et les acides gras oméga-3 si recommandés par un professionnel de santé
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Stress et manque de sommeil 
- Obésité et mauvaise alimentation 
- Certains médicaments ou déséquilibres hormonaux 
- Tabagisme et consommation excessive d'alcool
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: La progestérone joue un rôle central dans la grossesse en soutenant l'implantation embryonnaire et en maintenant le calme utérin. Elle module également les réponses immunitaires en affectant les cellules T auxiliaires et les cellules T régulatrices. Dans le cancer du sein, les récepteurs de la progestérone sont régulés à la hausse par les récepteurs des estrogènes, influençant le comportement des tumeurs et la réponse au traitement. Le gène du récepteur de la progestérone (PGR) code pour deux principales isoformes, PR-A et PR-B, qui ont des fonctions distinctes dans la croissance et la différenciation cellulaires.
biomarker.info.importance: Mesurer la progestérone est important car elle sert de biomarqueur pour la santé et les résultats de la grossesse. De faibles niveaux de progestérone ont été liés à l'accouchement prématuré et à l'échec précoce de la grossesse. De plus, les récepteurs de la progestérone sont significatifs dans le pronostic du cancer du sein, particulièrement dans les cas hormonodépendants, où une expression élevée des PR est associée à de meilleurs résultats.

biomarker.info.description: The Total Cholesterol / HDL Ratio is a biomarker that assesses cardiovascular risk by comparing total cholesterol levels to high-density lipoprotein (HDL) cholesterol levels. HDL is often referred to as 'good' cholesterol because it helps remove other forms of cholesterol from the bloodstream, reducing the risk of heart disease.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: A high Total Cholesterol / HDL Ratio is associated with increased risks of cardiovascular disease, including atherosclerosis and myocardial infarction. It also correlates with a higher risk of non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD)[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9099113/)[5](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30744645/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: A low Total Cholesterol / HDL Ratio generally indicates a lower risk of cardiovascular disease. However, there is limited evidence on specific health risks associated with very low ratios, as they are typically seen as beneficial.
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a healthy diet rich in fruits, vegetables, and whole grains 
- Engage in regular physical activity to improve HDL levels 
- Manage weight to reduce total cholesterol 
- Limit intake of saturated fats and trans fats 
- Consider omega-3 fatty acids for heart health
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- High intake of saturated and trans fats 
- Sedentary lifestyle 
- Obesity 
- Smoking 
- High consumption of processed foods
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: The Total Cholesterol / HDL Ratio is a significant predictor of cardiovascular risk because it reflects the balance between atherogenic (harmful) and anti-atherogenic (protective) cholesterol components. A higher ratio indicates a greater proportion of harmful cholesterol relative to protective HDL, which is associated with increased risk of atherosclerosis and cardiovascular events[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2747394/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9797665/). This ratio is also linked to the risk of non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD)[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9099113/)[5](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30744645/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring the Total Cholesterol / HDL Ratio is important because it provides a more accurate assessment of cardiovascular risk than measuring total cholesterol or HDL levels alone. This ratio is particularly useful for identifying individuals at risk of atherosclerosis and other cardiovascular diseases, even when their lipid profiles appear normal[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2747394/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9797665/).

biomarker.info.description: Le pourcentage de lymphocytes est un biomarqueur qui reflète la proportion de lymphocytes dans le sang, qui sont cruciaux pour la réponse adaptative du système immunitaire. Il aide à évaluer la fonction immunitaire et à prédire les résultats dans diverses maladies, y compris le cancer et les infections.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: Des pourcentages élevés de lymphocytes ne sont généralement pas nocifs mais peuvent indiquer une réponse immunitaire active, qui pourrait être observée dans des conditions comme les maladies auto-immunes ou les infections.
biomarker.info.risksLow: De faibles pourcentages de lymphocytes sont associés à une susceptibilité accrue aux infections, un mauvais pronostic du cancer, et une fragilité chez les personnes âgées[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6382732/)[8](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8293122/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintenir une alimentation équilibrée riche en fruits, légumes, et grains entiers 
- Rester hydraté 
- Participer à une activité physique régulière 
- Gérer le stress efficacement 
- Assurer un sommeil adéquat 
- Éviter le tabagisme et la consommation excessive d'alcool
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Alimentation pauvre en nutriments essentiels 
- Manque d'activité physique 
- Stress chronique 
- Tabagisme et consommation excessive d'alcool 
- Certains médicaments (par ex., immunosuppresseurs)
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Les lymphocytes sont des composants clés du système immunitaire adaptatif, impliqués dans la reconnaissance et l'élimination des pathogènes et des cellules cancéreuses. Le pourcentage de lymphocytes peut indiquer la capacité immunitaire de l'organisme et a été utilisé comme marqueur pronostique dans plusieurs maladies. Les changements dans les pourcentages de lymphocytes peuvent refléter l'inflammation, la suppression immunitaire ou la progression de la maladie[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8998851/)[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8980931/).
biomarker.info.importance: Mesurer le pourcentage de lymphocytes est important car il peut prédire les résultats des maladies et surveiller le statut immunitaire. Par exemple, dans le cancer du poumon, un pourcentage de lymphocytes plus élevé est associé à de meilleurs taux de survie[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8980931/). De plus, la lymphocytopénie (faible nombre de lymphocytes) est liée à un mauvais pronostic dans des conditions comme le cancer de l'ovaire[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6382732/).
