biomarker.info.description: Red Cell Distribution Width (RDW) is a hematological parameter that quantifies the variation in size of red blood cells (RBCs). It reflects anisocytosis, which is the presence of RBCs of unequal sizes. RDW is calculated from the standard deviation of RBC volume divided by the mean corpuscular volume (MCV), expressed as a percentage.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High RDW levels are linked to several risks including increased mortality rates from cardiovascular diseases, complications from chronic illnesses like diabetes or kidney disease, and poor prognosis following acute medical events such as ischemic strokes or sepsis.
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low levels of RDW are generally not associated with significant health risks; however, they may indicate a lack of variability among red blood cells that could mask underlying conditions related to effective erythropoiesis.
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Ensure adequate intake of iron-rich foods (e.g., lean meats, beans) 
- Consume foods rich in vitamin B12 (e.g., dairy products) 
- Include folate-rich foods (e.g., leafy greens) 
- Maintain hydration for optimal circulation 
- Regular physical activity to enhance overall metabolic health
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Nutritional deficiencies (iron, vitamin B12, folate) 
- Chronic inflammatory states 
- Kidney dysfunction leading to altered erythropoiesis 
- Certain medications affecting red blood cell production
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: RDW provides crucial information regarding erythrocyte size distribution, which can indicate underlying health issues. A high RDW suggests significant variability in RBC sizes due to factors like ineffective erythropoiesis or increased destruction of RBCs. This biomarker has gained attention for its role in predicting outcomes across various conditions such as heart disease, cancer, and inflammatory states. Studies have shown that elevated RDW correlates with adverse outcomes in critically ill patients and those with chronic diseases. Its utility extends beyond anemia diagnosis to serve as a prognostic marker for cardiovascular events and overall mortality risk.
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring RDW is essential because it serves as an indicator of various health conditions. Elevated RDW levels are associated with increased morbidity and mortality across multiple diseases, including cardiovascular disorders and anemia. It can provide insights into underlying pathologies such as nutritional deficiencies or chronic inflammation, making it a valuable tool for early diagnosis and risk stratification in clinical settings.

biomarker.info.description: Prostate-Specific Antigen (PSA) is a protein produced by prostate gland cells. It serves as a biomarker for prostate cancer detection and monitoring, aiding in the assessment of prostate health and potential malignancies.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High PSA levels are often indicative of potential malignancy but can also result from benign conditions like BPH or prostatitis. Elevated readings necessitate further investigation through biopsy to confirm or rule out cancer diagnosis.
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low PSA levels generally indicate lower risk for significant prostate pathology; however, they can also lead to missed diagnoses in cases where aggressive cancers exist despite low readings.
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a healthy diet rich in fruits and vegetables 
- Regular physical activity 
- Manage weight effectively 
- Limit intake of red meat and dairy products 
- Stay hydrated
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Age-related changes in the prostate 
- Prostatitis or inflammation 
- Benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) 
- Recent ejaculation prior to testing 
- Certain medications such as 5-alpha-reductase inhibitors
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: PSA is synthesized by both normal and malignant prostate cells, making it a non-specific marker for cancer. Its measurement has been pivotal since its introduction in the late 1980s as a screening tool for prostate cancer (PCa). Studies have shown that higher PSA levels correlate with advanced disease stages and poorer prognoses. However, factors such as age, benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH), prostatitis, ejaculation, and certain medications can influence PSA levels independently of cancer presence. Despite its utility in screening, challenges remain regarding specificity; many men with elevated PSA do not have PCa while some with normal levels may still harbor aggressive forms of the disease.
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring PSA levels is crucial for early detection of prostate cancer, which can significantly improve treatment outcomes. Elevated PSA levels are associated with increased risk of high-grade tumors and metastatic disease. Regular monitoring helps identify patients who may benefit from further diagnostic procedures like biopsies, thus facilitating timely intervention.

biomarker.info.description: Parathyroid hormone (PTH) is a key regulator of calcium and phosphorus levels in the body. It affects bone health by influencing osteoblast and osteoclast activity, and it plays a role in kidney function by regulating calcium reabsorption and vitamin D activation
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High PTH levels are associated with hyperparathyroidism, which can cause osteoporosis, kidney stones, and increased cardiovascular risk. Elevated PTH is also linked to higher mortality rates in older populations and those with chronic kidney disease[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3980926/)[4](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27653840/)[7](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9693802/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low PTH levels can lead to hypocalcemia, which may cause muscle cramps, spasms, and neurological symptoms like tingling and numbness. Hypoparathyroidism, characterized by low PTH, can result from surgical removal of the parathyroid glands or autoimmune disorders[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3980926/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain adequate vitamin D levels through sun exposure, supplements, or fortified foods 
- Ensure sufficient calcium intake from dairy products or supplements 
- Limit phosphorus intake if necessary, especially in kidney disease 
- Regular exercise to support bone health
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Vitamin D deficiency 
- Chronic kidney disease 
- Excessive phosphorus intake 
- Lack of calcium in the diet 
- Certain medications affecting calcium metabolism
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: PTH is crucial for maintaining calcium homeostasis. It increases calcium absorption in the gut by stimulating the conversion of vitamin D to its active form, enhances calcium reabsorption in the kidneys, and promotes bone resorption to release calcium into the bloodstream[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3980926/)[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31008771/). PTH also influences the expression of fibroblast growth factor-23 (FGF-23), which is involved in phosphate metabolism[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3980926/). The hormone's role in heart failure is linked to its association with brain natriuretic peptide levels, a marker of heart failure severity[3](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22875486/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring PTH is important because it helps in diagnosing and managing conditions like hyperparathyroidism, which can lead to bone diseases and kidney stones. Elevated PTH levels are also associated with increased mortality risk and are used as a biomarker in heart failure, indicating potential cardiovascular complications[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3980926/)[3](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22875486/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6951227/).

biomarker.info.description: Le calcium est un biomarqueur crucial impliqué dans de nombreux processus physiologiques, y compris la santé osseuse, la contraction musculaire, et la fonction nerveuse. Il est essentiel pour maintenir des os et des dents solides, et sa forme ionisée joue un rôle vital dans diverses fonctions corporelles.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: Les niveaux élevés de calcium (hypercalcémie) peuvent causer des symptômes tels que des nausées, des vomissements, et de la confusion. Elle est généralement associée à des conditions telles que l'hyperparathyroïdie et certains cancers[8](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5995116/). Un calcium sérique élevé peut également être lié à une inflammation chronique et à de mauvais résultats dans certains cancers[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8107585/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Les faibles niveaux de calcium (hypocalcémie) peuvent entraîner des crampes musculaires, de la faiblesse, et des symptômes neurologiques. Elle est souvent associée à des conditions comme l'hypoparathyroïdie et l'insuffisance rénale chronique[8](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5995116/). Dans des maladies comme la COVID-19 et la tuberculose, de faibles niveaux de calcium sérique sont liés à une gravité accrue[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7343468/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10778644/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintenir une alimentation équilibrée riche en calcium (par ex., produits laitiers, légumes à feuilles) 
- Assurer un apport adéquat en vitamine D pour l'absorption du calcium 
- Participer à une activité physique régulière pour soutenir la santé osseuse 
- Limiter l'apport excessif de caféine et d'acide phosphorique, qui peuvent interférer avec l'absorption du calcium
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Faible apport alimentaire en calcium 
- Carence en vitamine D 
- Consommation excessive de caféine et d'acide phosphorique 
- Manque d'activité physique 
- Certains médicaments (par ex., les corticostéroïdes)
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Le calcium est un élément clé dans la physiologie humaine, sa forme ionisée étant étroitement régulée dans le sang. Il est impliqué dans la contraction musculaire, la transmission neuronale, et la fonction des cellules immunitaires. Les biomarqueurs comme le calcium sérique et les métabolites urinaires (par ex., la pseudouridine et le citrate) peuvent aider à évaluer le statut et la carence en calcium[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3652781/)[8](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5995116/). La dyshoméostasie du calcium est associée au vieillissement et aux maladies neurodégénératives comme la maladie d'Alzheimer[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7836067/).
biomarker.info.importance: Mesurer les niveaux de calcium est important car cela peut indiquer des carences nutritionnelles, des problèmes de santé osseuse, et divers états pathologiques. Le statut du calcium est lié à la gravité clinique et au pronostic dans des maladies comme la COVID-19 et la tuberculose. Il joue également un rôle dans la régulation immunitaire et l'inflammation tumorale, en faisant un marqueur précieux pour la gravité et la progression des maladies[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7343468/)[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8107585/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10778644/).

biomarker.info.description: Estimated Glomerular Filtration Rate (eGFR) is a biomarker that measures kidney function by estimating the rate at which the kidneys filter waste from the blood. It is crucial for assessing the health of the kidneys and diagnosing conditions like chronic kidney disease (CKD).
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High eGFR values are less commonly associated with health risks but may indicate overestimation due to factors like muscle mass or certain medications. However, high eGFR is not typically a concern in clinical practice[7](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11262368/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low eGFR levels indicate impaired kidney function, which can lead to complications such as fluid buildup, electrolyte imbalances, and increased risk of cardiovascular diseases and mortality[7](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11262368/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a healthy diet low in sodium and protein 
- Stay hydrated to support kidney function 
- Exercise regularly to improve overall health 
- Manage blood pressure and diabetes through lifestyle changes and medication if necessary 
- Avoid smoking and excessive alcohol consumption
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- High blood pressure 
- Diabetes 
- Obesity 
- Smoking 
- Excessive alcohol consumption 
- Certain medications (e.g., NSAIDs) 
- Family history of kidney disease
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: eGFR is calculated using formulas like the CKD-EPI equation, which incorporates variables such as age, sex, race, and serum creatinine levels. It reflects the sum of the filtration rates of all functioning nephrons in the kidneys. eGFR serves as a prognostic marker for cardiovascular events and mortality, and it is essential for therapeutic decisions in patients with CKD[7](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11262368/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring eGFR is important because it helps diagnose and monitor chronic kidney disease, predict cardiovascular events, and determine the risk of end-stage kidney disease (ESKD) and mortality. It is also used to adjust medication dosages and monitor treatment effects in clinical settings[7](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11262368/).

biomarker.info.description: The Total Cholesterol / HDL Ratio is a biomarker that assesses cardiovascular risk by comparing total cholesterol levels to high-density lipoprotein (HDL) cholesterol levels. HDL is often referred to as 'good' cholesterol because it helps remove other forms of cholesterol from the bloodstream, reducing the risk of heart disease.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: A high Total Cholesterol / HDL Ratio is associated with increased risks of cardiovascular disease, including atherosclerosis and myocardial infarction. It also correlates with a higher risk of non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD)[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9099113/)[5](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30744645/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: A low Total Cholesterol / HDL Ratio generally indicates a lower risk of cardiovascular disease. However, there is limited evidence on specific health risks associated with very low ratios, as they are typically seen as beneficial.
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a healthy diet rich in fruits, vegetables, and whole grains 
- Engage in regular physical activity to improve HDL levels 
- Manage weight to reduce total cholesterol 
- Limit intake of saturated fats and trans fats 
- Consider omega-3 fatty acids for heart health
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- High intake of saturated and trans fats 
- Sedentary lifestyle 
- Obesity 
- Smoking 
- High consumption of processed foods
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: The Total Cholesterol / HDL Ratio is a significant predictor of cardiovascular risk because it reflects the balance between atherogenic (harmful) and anti-atherogenic (protective) cholesterol components. A higher ratio indicates a greater proportion of harmful cholesterol relative to protective HDL, which is associated with increased risk of atherosclerosis and cardiovascular events[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2747394/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9797665/). This ratio is also linked to the risk of non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD)[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9099113/)[5](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30744645/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring the Total Cholesterol / HDL Ratio is important because it provides a more accurate assessment of cardiovascular risk than measuring total cholesterol or HDL levels alone. This ratio is particularly useful for identifying individuals at risk of atherosclerosis and other cardiovascular diseases, even when their lipid profiles appear normal[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2747394/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9797665/).

biomarker.info.description: Magnesium is a crucial mineral involved in numerous physiological processes, including enzyme activity, energy production, and neuromuscular function. It serves as a cofactor for many enzymes and is essential for maintaining cellular integrity and overall health.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High magnesium levels (hypermagnesemia) are less common but can pose serious risks, especially in individuals with impaired renal function or those receiving high doses of magnesium supplements[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11444808/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low magnesium levels (hypomagnesemia) can lead to neuromuscular symptoms, cardiovascular issues, and metabolic complications. It is particularly risky for individuals with chronic illnesses or those experiencing malnutrition[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11444808/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Include magnesium-rich foods in your diet, such as dark leafy greens, nuts, and whole grains 
- Consider magnesium supplements if dietary intake is insufficient 
- Maintain adequate hydration to support magnesium absorption 
- Limit alcohol consumption, which can impair magnesium absorption
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Poor dietary intake 
- Chronic illnesses 
- Malnutrition 
- Impaired renal function 
- Excessive alcohol consumption 
- Certain medications that interfere with magnesium absorption
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Magnesium is vital for various biochemical processes, including those related to energy metabolism and neuromuscular function. However, diagnosing magnesium status can be challenging due to its compartmentalization in the body. Biomarkers like Na/K ATPase, thromboxane B2, C-reactive protein, and endothelin-1 have been proposed to better reflect magnesium's role in biochemical processes[1](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15637224/)[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6163803/). Ionized magnesium is considered a more accurate measure of bioavailability compared to total magnesium[8](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8370522/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring magnesium is important because it helps assess nutritional status and diagnose deficiencies, which are common among populations with chronic illnesses or malnutrition. Magnesium plays a significant role in cardiovascular health, and its levels can influence disease prognosis and management[1](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15637224/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11444808/).

biomarker.info.description: Mean Platelet Volume (MPV) is a measure of the average size of platelets in the blood. It reflects platelet activity and is used as a biomarker for various health conditions, including cardiovascular diseases and inflammatory processes
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High MPV levels are associated with increased risks of cardiovascular diseases, such as myocardial infarction and stroke, as well as other conditions like diabetes and certain cancers[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31148950/)[7](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10909253/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low MPV levels have been observed in conditions like tuberculosis during disease exacerbation and certain neoplastic diseases, suggesting reduced platelet activity or production[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31148950/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a healthy lifestyle to reduce inflammation and cardiovascular risk 
- Avoid smoking and excessive alcohol consumption 
- Engage in regular physical activity to improve cardiovascular health 
- Manage stress levels
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Smoking 
- Excessive alcohol consumption 
- Poor diet 
- Lack of physical activity 
- Stress 
- Certain medications
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: MPV is calculated during routine blood tests and reflects the size of platelets, which are essential for blood clotting and inflammation. Larger platelets are more active and contain more prothrombotic material, making them more likely to aggregate and form clots[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5094934/)[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3739454/). MPV is inversely related to platelet count under normal conditions but can be altered in various pathologies, indicating changes in platelet production or activation[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6501263/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring MPV is important because it provides insights into platelet activity, which is crucial for understanding the risk and prognosis of cardiovascular events, inflammatory diseases, and certain cancers. MPV can serve as a predictive and prognostic biomarker, helping in early detection and management of these conditions[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6501263/)[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31148950/).

biomarker.info.description: Calcitonin is a hormone produced by the thyroid gland's C-cells, acting as an anti-hypercalcemic agent (helping to lower blood calcium levels). It is a key biomarker for diagnosing and monitoring medullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC), a type of thyroid cancer
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High calcitonin levels are indicative of MTC or other conditions like C-cell hyperplasia. Elevated levels can also occur due to secondary factors such as hypercalcemia, renal insufficiency, or certain medications[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9125613/)[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3835110/).
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low calcitonin levels are generally not associated with specific health risks but may indicate a lack of C-cell activity or thyroid function issues. However, low levels in the context of MTC could suggest successful treatment or remission[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8602843/).
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a healthy thyroid function through balanced nutrition and lifestyle 
- Avoid smoking, which can increase calcitonin levels 
- Manage body weight, as increased BMI can affect calcitonin levels 
- Regular health check-ups for early detection of thyroid issues
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Smoking 
- Increased body mass index (BMI) 
- Certain medications (e.g., β-blockers) 
- Renal insufficiency 
- Hypercalcemia 
- False-positive results from assay variability
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Calcitonin is a 32-amino acid polypeptide hormone with a disulfide bridge, primarily secreted by the parafollicular C-cells of the thyroid gland. It acts through the calcitonin receptor, influencing calcium metabolism. Calcitonin levels are measured using immunoassays, which can vary in sensitivity and specificity. It is used for diagnosing and monitoring MTC, often in conjunction with other tests like fine-needle aspiration cytology[1](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26494386/)[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9125613/)[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3835110/).
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring calcitonin is crucial for the early detection and management of medullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC). It helps in diagnosing MTC before symptoms appear, allowing for timely intervention. Elevated calcitonin levels can indicate MTC or other conditions like C-cell hyperplasia, making it a valuable tool in thyroid health assessment[1](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26494386/)[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3835110/)[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7075519/).

biomarker.info.description: Lymphocytes are a type of white blood cell crucial for the immune response, playing key roles in recognizing and responding to pathogens. They include T cells (which help regulate immune responses), B cells (which produce antibodies), and natural killer cells (which attack infected or cancerous cells).
biomarker.info.risksHigh: High lymphocyte levels (lymphocytosis) can indicate underlying health issues such as chronic inflammatory conditions or hematological malignancies like leukemia. Elevated levels might also occur during acute viral infections but could signify more serious conditions if persistent.
biomarker.info.risksLow: Low lymphocyte levels (lymphopenia) can lead to increased susceptibility to infections due to a weakened immune response. This condition may arise from various causes such as viral infections like HIV/AIDS or autoimmune diseases where the body mistakenly attacks its own tissues.
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintain a balanced diet rich in vitamins A, C, D, E 
- Engage in regular physical activity 
- Manage stress through mindfulness practices 
- Ensure adequate sleep 
- Avoid smoking and limit alcohol consumption
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Chronic stress 
- Poor nutrition lacking essential vitamins 
- Sedentary lifestyle 
- Certain medications such as corticosteroids that suppress immunity
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: Lymphocytes are categorized into three main types: T lymphocytes (T cells), B lymphocytes (B cells), and natural killer (NK) cells. T cells can be further divided into helper T cells that assist other immune responses and cytotoxic T cells that kill infected or cancerous host cells. B cells are responsible for antibody production which neutralizes pathogens. The balance between different types of lymphocytes is crucial; for instance, an increase in cytotoxic T cell activity may indicate an active infection or malignancy while a decrease may suggest immunosuppression or chronic disease states. Lymphocyte counts can be influenced by various factors including age, stress levels, nutritional status, infections like COVID-19 where low counts have been associated with severe disease outcomes.
biomarker.info.importance: Measuring lymphocyte levels is vital as they serve as indicators of immune system health. Abnormal lymphocyte counts can signal various health issues, including infections, autoimmune disorders, and cancers. Monitoring these levels helps in diagnosing conditions like HIV/AIDS, assessing the effectiveness of treatments such as chemotherapy or immunotherapy, and predicting patient outcomes.

biomarker.info.description: La progestérone est une hormone stéroïde cruciale pour le maintien de la grossesse et la régulation du cycle menstruel. Elle se lie aux récepteurs de la progestérone (PR), influençant diverses fonctions corporelles, y compris les réponses immunitaires et la croissance cellulaire.
biomarker.info.risksHigh: Des niveaux élevés de progestérone ne sont généralement pas nocifs mais peuvent être associés à certaines conditions comme l'hyperprolactinémie ou le syndrome des ovaires polykystiques (SOPK) dans certains contextes. Cependant, les risques sont plus liés à l'équilibre de la progestérone qu'à ses niveaux absolus.
biomarker.info.risksLow: Les faibles niveaux de progestérone sont associés à des risques accrus d'accouchement prématuré et d'échec précoce de la grossesse. Chez les femmes non enceintes, une faible progestérone peut perturber les cycles menstruels et la fertilité.
biomarker.info.positiveImpacts:
- Maintenir un poids sain pour soutenir l'équilibre hormonal 
- Participer à une activité physique régulière pour améliorer la santé globale 
- Assurer un sommeil adéquat et une gestion du stress 
- Envisager des suppléments alimentaires comme la vitamine D et les acides gras oméga-3 si recommandés par un professionnel de santé
biomarker.info.negativeImpacts:
- Stress et manque de sommeil 
- Obésité et mauvaise alimentation 
- Certains médicaments ou déséquilibres hormonaux 
- Tabagisme et consommation excessive d'alcool
biomarker.info.scientificDetails: La progestérone joue un rôle central dans la grossesse en soutenant l'implantation embryonnaire et en maintenant le calme utérin. Elle module également les réponses immunitaires en affectant les cellules T auxiliaires et les cellules T régulatrices. Dans le cancer du sein, les récepteurs de la progestérone sont régulés à la hausse par les récepteurs des estrogènes, influençant le comportement des tumeurs et la réponse au traitement. Le gène du récepteur de la progestérone (PGR) code pour deux principales isoformes, PR-A et PR-B, qui ont des fonctions distinctes dans la croissance et la différenciation cellulaires.
biomarker.info.importance: Mesurer la progestérone est important car elle sert de biomarqueur pour la santé et les résultats de la grossesse. De faibles niveaux de progestérone ont été liés à l'accouchement prématuré et à l'échec précoce de la grossesse. De plus, les récepteurs de la progestérone sont significatifs dans le pronostic du cancer du sein, particulièrement dans les cas hormonodépendants, où une expression élevée des PR est associée à de meilleurs résultats.
